Example Data Loading¶

# Read loom file using Scanpy, this step will take a while due to the high number of cells
# Maybe we should consider downsampling the data set?
loom_filepath = "data/cells_anndata.loom"
print("Reading loom file . . .")
cells = sp.read_loom(loom_filepath, sparse=False)
print("Complete!")

In [14]:
# Here I'm going to create a function to clean up the anndata object, only keeping obs we are interested in since there are so many we won't use
# This will also shrink the size of the object if we were to write it to disk
def filter_anndata_object(keep, adata):
    adata_copy = adata.copy()
    keys = list(adata_copy.obs.keys())
    for key in keys:
        if key not in keep:
            del adata_copy.obs[key]
    return adata_copy
In [15]:
# Define the list of obs to keep and then do the filtering
obs_to_keep = ['CellFromTumor', 'nCount_RNA', 'nCount_SCT', 'nFeature_RNA', 'nFeature_SCT', 'nGene', 'nUMI', 'orig_ident', 'percent_mito', 'percent_ribo', 'seurat_clusters', 
               'tissue', 'type']
cells_cleaned = filter_anndata_object(obs_to_keep, cells)
del cells_cleaned.layers['scale_data']
cells_cleaned_final = cells_cleaned[~cells_cleaned.obs['type'].isin(['?'])].copy()
cells_cleaned_final
